sentences: Halid Bešlić (Bosnian pronunciation: [xǎːlid bɛ̂ʃlitɕ]; born 20 November 1953) is a Bosnian folk singer and musician who has been performing professionally since 1979.
Halid Bešlić (Bosnian pronunciation: [xǎːlid bɛ̂ʃlitɕ]; born 20 November 1953) is a Bosnian folk singer and musician who has been performing professionally since 1979.
Halid's singing career was one of the most successful in Yugoslavia, and continues today throughout the entire Balkan region.
His father Mujo Bešlić, a military man, died on 1 April 2016 at the age of 83 in a Sarajevo hospital.
Halid, who was on tour in the United States at the time, managed to arrive to the funeral held in a village by Olovo, where Mujo had lived since the start of the Bosnian War in 1992.
After several years, his first musical releases were eight singles between 1979 and 1982, with his first studio album, entitled Sijedi starac (White Haired Old Man), being released in 1981.

After several years, his first musical releases were eight singles between 1979 and 1982, with his first studio album, entitled Sijedi starac (White Haired Old Man), being released in 1981.

By 1984, he started becoming more and more well known, with popular songs such as "Neću, neću dijamante" (I Don't Want, I Don't Want Diamonds) and "Budi budi uvijek srećna" (Always, Always Be a Happy Woman) being heard all over Yugoslavia.

Bešlić released eight albums during the 1980s, with hit songs including "Vraćam se majci u Bosnu" (I Am Returning to my Mother in Bosnia), "Sjećam se" (I Remember), "Hej, zoro, ne svani" (Hey, Morning, Don't Rise) and "Eh, kad bi ti" (If Only You Would).

Bešlić released eight albums during the 1980s, with hit songs including "Vraćam se majci u Bosnu" (I Am Returning to my Mother in Bosnia), "Sjećam se" (I Remember), "Hej, zoro, ne svani" (Hey, Morning, Don't Rise) and "Eh, kad bi ti" (If Only You Would).
He also had several hit songs in the 2000s and 2010s.
The 2003 album Prvi poljubac featured the hit song of the same name.

The song "Miljacka", named after the Bosnian river, was featured on his 2007 album Halid 08 and the songs "Štiklom o kamen" (High Heels on Stone) and "Kad zaigra srce od meraka" (When the Heart Dances with Joy) were featured on Romanija (2013).

The song "Miljacka", named after the Bosnian river, was featured on his 2007 album Halid 08 and the songs "Štiklom o kamen" (High Heels on Stone) and "Kad zaigra srce od meraka" (When the Heart Dances with Joy) were featured on Romanija (2013).
The album Trebević, named after the Bosnian mountain, was released in February 2020.
Bešlić married his wife Sejda in November 1977.
In the 1990s, during the breakup of Yugoslavia, Bosnia went into war and Bešlić staged more than 500 humanitarian concerts across Europe for the victims in his home country.
In 2015, Bešlić acquired Croatian citizenship.
=== 2009 car wreck ===
On 10 March 2009, Bešlić left his gas station at around 4 in the morning, and ran his Škoda Superb off the road, due to icy conditions, and crashed.
On 10 March 2009, Bešlić left his gas station at around 4 in the morning, and ran his Škoda Superb off the road, due to icy conditions, and crashed.
Notably, he held a major concert in Zagreb at the end of October 2009.
He had earlier survived a car wreck in 1986 with the singer Suzana Mančić.
